After two days of MPs debating his state of the nation address, President Cyril Ramaphosa got the chance to respond on Wednesday. He's said that even though people disagree in parliament, no one should be left behind. eNCA reporter Ayesha Ismail has been following the story. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - After two days of MPs debating his state of the nation address, President Cyril Ramaphosa finally got the chance to respond to the question: What keeps him up at night? He's told the media that the state of the country’s economy is one of his biggest headaches. READ: Ramaphosa says economy has become less competitive He was responding on a range of topics, including job creation and the economy. "What keeps me awake at night... I am seriously kept awake at night. It's the state of our economy, the state of unemployment," he said. "It's very difficult to have 11 million people out of work.. people who are not economically engaged in any economic activity. That is enough to keep me awake at night and it concerns me a great deal."